solutions.content:
**What does the question ask for?**
The question asks us to determine whether the end index is reachable from index 0.

**How may we approach this problem?**
The basic idea for this problem is to check the reachability of intermediate indexes to determine the reachability of some index

# Approach #1 : Recursion + Visited

Write another method wherein we check whether the end index is reachable from the current index
If we can reach to the current index from 0 and then from current index to end index,
then we can surely reach from 0 to end index (0-> current index -> end index)

**What is the purpose of visited?**
While calculating the reach. we may end up at the same index multiple times. If that index has been processed earlier -> Either it would have returned true, in which case, no more calculations would have been done, but since we encountered this index again, means that its result was false.

```
class Solution {
    boolean[] visited;
    public boolean canJump(int[] nums) {
        int len = nums.length;
        visited = new boolean[len];
        return canJump(0,len, nums, visited);
    }
    private boolean canJump(int ind, int len, int[] nums, boolean[] visited){
        if(ind>=len-1){
            return true;
        }
        if(visited[ind]){
            return false;
        }
        visited[ind]=true;
        int maxJumps = nums[ind];
        if(maxJumps==0){
            return false;
        }
        for(int i=maxJumps;i>=1;i--){
            if(canJump(ind+i, len, nums, visited)){
                return true;
            }
        }
        return false;
    }
}
```

# Approach #2 : Bottom-up DP/Tabulation

**How else can we solve the problem?**
If the problem is solvable recursively, there will be an iterative solution as well.
The idea for this approach is:
Maintain an array to check whether the current index is reachable from zero

**How will we update reachable array?**
We will use the idea of intermediate indexes:
Say we want to update index i
We will consider some intermediate index j, s.t., 0<=j<i
Then:
a) We will check that j is reachable from zero (using our reachable array)
b) We will check that i is reachable from j (Maximum index reachable from j = j+nums[j], if i<=max_index, then i is reachable otherwise not)

```
class Solution {
    public boolean canJump(int[] nums) {
        int len = nums.length;
        if(len==1){
            return true;
        }
        boolean[] isReachableFromZero = new boolean[len];
        isReachableFromZero[0] = true;
        for(int i=1;i<len;i++){
            for(int j=i-1;j>=0;j--){
                // If j is reachable from zero
                // and from j, we can reach i
                // Means we can reach i from Zero
                if(isReachableFromZero[j]&&j+nums[j]>=i){
                    isReachableFromZero[i]=true;
                    break;
                }
            }
        }
        return isReachableFromZero[len-1];
    }
}
```

# Approach #3: No DP
**What can we improve in the previous approach?**
What if instead of maintaining an array to check the reachability, we maintain a single variable that determines the maximum reachable index from 0 at a given iteration? In that case, we can simply check if the current index is within reach or out of reach, all the while updating max reach if current index is within reach.

```
class Solution {
    public boolean canJump(int[] nums) {
        int len = nums.length;
        if(len==1){
            return true;
        }
        int maxReachFromZero = 0;
        for(int i=0;i<len;i++){
            if(i<=maxReachFromZero){
                maxReachFromZero = Math.max(maxReachFromZero,i+nums[i]);
            } else{
                return false;
            }
            if(maxReachFromZero>=len-1){
                break;
            }
        }
        return true;
    }
}
```

**References:**
1.  https://leetcode.com/problems/jump-game/discuss/1819771/C%2B%2B-Memoization-(Top-Down)-and-Tabulation-(Bottom-Up)
2. https://leetcode.com/problems/jump-game/discuss/1820513/C%2B%2B-No-DP-Needed-Single-Traversal

