**Thumbs up if you find this helpful** 👍

This solution is inspired by the hint ```Consider each node in the stack having a minimum value.```

The main idea of this solution is to have a way to keep track of the minimum value every time an item is pushed onto the stack. 

When a new value is pushed onto the stack, it is checked against the last minimum to see if the current value is a minimum. Every time a new item is added, we keep track of the minimum value for each push.

In both solutions:
* When the ```Top``` function is called, the current top value is returned.
* When the ```GetMin``` function is called, the minimum value at the time top value was pushed onto the stack is returned
* When the ```Push``` function is called, the value and the current minimum value is pushed onto the stack

**1. Using Stack**

In this solution, we use a stack<pair<int, int>> to keep track of the current item pushed onto the stack, and the minimum value at the time the item was pushed onto the stack.

```
public class MinStack {
    private Stack<KeyValuePair<int, int>> data;

    /** initialize your data structure here. */
    public MinStack() {
        // Initialize the stack
        // The pair key is the stack value
        // The pair value is the current stack minimum value
        data = new Stack<KeyValuePair<int, int>>();
    }

    public void Push(int val) {
        // Determine minimum value.
        // If the stack is not empty, compare against the last min value
        var currentMinValue = val;    
        if (data.Count > 0) {
            currentMinValue = Math.Min(currentMinValue, GetMin());
        }

        // Add new entry to the stack, saving the value and current minimum
        data.Push(new KeyValuePair<int, int>(val, currentMinValue));
    }

    public void Pop() {
        data.Pop();
    }

    public int Top() {
        // Return the current top value
        return data.Peek().Key;
    }

    public int GetMin() {        
        // Return the current minimum value
        return data.Peek().Value;        
    }
}
 ```


**2. Using List**

In this solution, we use a list<pair<int, int>> to keep track of the current item pushed onto the stack, and the minimum value at the time the item was pushed onto the stack.

 ```
public class MinStack {
    private List<KeyValuePair<int, int>> data;

    /** initialize your data structure here. */
    public MinStack() {
        // Initialize the list
        // The pair key is the stack value
        // The pair value is the current stack minimum value
        data = new List<KeyValuePair<int, int>>();
    }

    public void Push(int val) {
        // Determine minimum value.
        // If the stack is not empty, compare against the last min value
        var currentMinValue = val;    
        if (data.Count > 0) {
            currentMinValue = Math.Min(currentMinValue, GetMin());
        }

        // Add new entry to the stack, saving the value and current minimum
        data.Add(new KeyValuePair<int, int>(val, currentMinValue));
    }

    public void Pop() {
        data.RemoveAt(data.Count - 1);
    }

    public int Top() {
        // Return the current top value
        return data[data.Count - 1].Key;
    }

    public int GetMin() {        
        // Return the current minimum value
        return data[data.Count - 1].Value;        
    }
}
```

