The solution is a bit complex. But it is very fast.
The solution lies in how you store the data.

To store every user's following list. Use unordered_set for fast insert and remove:
**unordered_map<int, unordered_set< int>>**

Since tweetIds can be any value, the time at which it is posted is important. We store tweet info in vector for fast access:
**vector<int> tweetData;**
**int tweetTime;**

To store every user's tweets, we keep a map with Tweet*. Every new tweet will be added at the front for recent tweet retrieval
**unordered_map<int, Tweet\*> userTweets;**

**follow** and **unfollow** api are pretty straightforward. Just insert and erase in the unordered_set of follower

**postTweet:**
Everytime a user post a tweets, we push its value in the vector. The index(tweetTime) of vector is stored in user Tweets data. We create a new tweet with the index and add it the front of Tweet Linked List of user.

**getNewsFeed:**
Remember we only need 10 recent tweets.
Cases:
1. All 10 tweets are of same user/followee id.
2. There are less than 10 tweets.
3. All recent tweets are distributed across user and followees.

We take a priority queue(maxHeap) and push all head pointers of user's Tweet linked list and all followees' Tweet linked lists. This is very similar to "Merge K sorted lists" problem.

We start popping from priority queue and stop if 10 count is reached or priority queue has no more tweets left.

Everytime we pop, we take tweet value from Tweet vector (tweetData) for the index popped and if there exists a next pointer in that Linked List, we push it to priority queue, thereby ensuring the conditions that there can be multiple recent tweets from same person.

***Note:** There is still optimization scope as we are storing more than 10 tweets for each user in the Linked List. Suggestions are welcome. And yes, I am not freeing the memory taken for each Tweet.*
```
struct Tweet {
    int id;
    Tweet* next;
};
struct cmp {
    bool operator() (Tweet* t1, Tweet* t2) {
        return t1->id < t2->id;
    }
};
class Twitter {
private:
    unordered_map<int,unordered_set<int>> following;
    vector<int> tweetData;
    int tweetTime;
    unordered_map<int, Tweet*> userTweets;
public:
    Twitter() {
        tweetTime = 0;
    }

    void postTweet(int userId, int tweetId) {        
        tweetData.push_back(tweetId);
        Tweet* t = new Tweet();
        t->id = tweetTime;
        t->next = userTweets[userId];
        userTweets[userId] = t;
        tweetTime++;
    }

    vector<int> getNewsFeed(int userId) {
        vector<int> ans;
        priority_queue<Tweet*, vector<Tweet*>, cmp> pq; 
        if(userTweets[userId] != NULL) {
            pq.push(userTweets[userId]);
        }
        for(auto it = following[userId].begin(); it != following[userId].end(); it++) {
            if(userTweets[*it] != NULL) {
                pq.push(userTweets[*it]);
            }
        }
        int count = 0;
        while(count < 10 && !pq.empty()) {
            Tweet* t = pq.top();
            pq.pop();
            if(t->next) pq.push(t->next);
            ans.push_back(tweetData[t->id]);
            ++count;
        }
        return ans;
    }

    void follow(int followerId, int followeeId) {
        following[followerId].insert(followeeId);

    }

    void unfollow(int followerId, int followeeId) {
        following[followerId].erase(followeeId);
    }
};
