# Intuition
Based on the question, we first need to match the possible ways to concent the children. We can't go with $$O(n2)$$ approach as the constrains for each input is $$O(10^4)$$, so this problem must be solved in $$O(nlogn)$$. 

How about we sort the arrays and match the possible ways.

First, I has sort both the arrays g and s. Once the arrays are sorted we traverse the arrays one by one and count the values where (g<=s).
But, there is an issue with the mapping, all the possible values are being mapped to wrong position.

Eg: 
s - 5 6 7 8 - is mapped to 
g - 7 8 9 10
here 7 is mapped to 5 and 8 is mapped to 6, and we get the result as 0.

So, we can match the shortest value of the g(greed) array to the match position.

which will look as,

s - 5 6 7 8 - is mapped to 
g - - -  7 8 9 10 - where the values are correctly mapped.

# Approach
First we sort both the arrays,
set a counter to count the maximum content of the children.
we want to iterate to the end of the arrays at the same time, So we go with while loop.
So, variable $$i$$ pointer for g(greed) and $$j$$ pointer for s(size).

iterating the while loop:
if the value of g is less than or equal to s then we move both the pointers of g and s along with incrementing the counter.
else we only move the j pointer of s to match the g value. Hoping in turn, the greater value of s will match with smaller value of g.

finally we return count.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
$$O(nlogn)$$ + $$O(nlogn)$$ - as we sort both the arrays,
the iteration is $$O(g+s)$$, but it is $$O(n)$$ less than $$O(nlogn)$$
So $$O(nlogn)$$ is the time complexity

- Space complexity:
$$O(1)$$ - We are not using as additional space. Only pointers to iterate.

